You are grading insights extracted from a podcast episode.

Grade each insight on how much genuine knowledge it carries for someone who has NOT heard the
episode. Judge the CLAIM, not the wording. A fluent sentence that says nothing scores low.

  3 = CORE. A substantive claim about the world: a decision, deal, launch, departure or result;
      a concrete number or finding; a causal argument ("X happened because Y"); a substantive
      position a named person took, or a real disagreement between speakers. Belongs in a
      briefing on this episode.
  2 = USEFUL. A real supporting detail or secondary point. Specific and true, but not central.
  1 = MINOR. Incidental, obvious, or so generic it could apply to many episodes on the topic
      ("AI is advancing rapidly", "this raises important questions", "the hosts discuss the news").
  0 = FILLER. Not an insight: chit-chat, an ad or sponsor read, a topic label, a restatement of
      the episode title, or a claim with no content.

Be strict. Most episodes contain only a handful of 3s.

Return ONLY a JSON object mapping each insight id to its integer tier. No commentary, no
markdown fences.

Example shape (ids will differ):
{"i0": 3, "i1": 1, "i2": 2}

INSIGHTS:
{{ insights }}
